  "footnotes": [
    "Frisian Kingdom (c.500–734): the Frisii controlled the North Sea coast from modern Flanders to northern Germany; they were the last Germanic people in the Low Countries to be conquered by the Franks; Charles Martel defeated King Radbod's successors and Boniface's mission Christianized the region",
    "County of Flanders (862–1384): one of the wealthiest territories in medieval Europe; Bruges and Ghent were among the largest cities north of the Alps; Flemish cloth trade with English wool created Europe's first proto-industrial economy; the Battle of the Golden Spurs (1302) saw Flemish urban militia defeat French cavalry — a foundational event in Flemish identity",
    "Burgundian Netherlands (1384–1477): the Valois Dukes of Burgundy assembled the Low Countries through marriage, purchase, and war; the Pragmatic Sanction of 1549 under Charles V formally unified the Seventeen Provinces; this created the administrative framework that later defined both the Netherlands and Belgium",
    "Dutch Republic (1581–1795): the Republic of the Seven United Provinces was the first major republic in modern European history; the Dutch Golden Age produced Rembrandt, Vermeer, Spinoza, and Huygens; the VOC (Dutch East India Company, 1602) was the world's first publicly traded company; Amsterdam became the global center of finance",
    "Belgian Revolution (1830): the southern provinces revolted against Dutch rule driven by linguistic, religious (Catholic vs Protestant), and economic grievances; the great powers recognized Belgian independence and guaranteed its perpetual neutrality (violated by Germany in 1914); Leopold I of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha became the first King",
    "Congo Free State (1885–1908): Leopold II's personal colony in central Africa was notorious for brutal exploitation of the rubber trade; international outcry (E.D. Morel, Roger Casement) forced Belgium to annex the territory as Belgian Congo in 1908; the Congo gained independence in 1960 amid political crisis",
    "Benelux (1948): Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg formed the first post-war European economic union, serving as a model and catalyst for the broader European Coal and Steel Community (1952) and eventually the European Economic Community (1957); all three host major EU institutions today"
  ]
}
